00:43:03.050 --> 00:43:05.430
Well, I mean we love to hear it.

00:43:05.430 --> 00:43:07.160
It's a great story, right?

00:43:07.160 --> 00:43:11.910
I mean it's amazing
but you're right.

00:43:11.910 --> 00:43:15.930
Sometimes the
mistake people make

00:43:15.930 --> 00:43:19.090
is closing the door too soon.

00:43:19.090 --> 00:43:21.530
A lot of kids are
early bloomers.

00:43:21.530 --> 00:43:24.140
A lot are bloomed right in
the middle, most of them.

00:43:24.140 --> 00:43:26.120
Some are late bloomers.

00:43:26.120 --> 00:43:29.450
The trick for parents
is to be watching

00:43:29.450 --> 00:43:33.720
for those sparks of interest and
talent and to pick up on them

00:43:33.720 --> 00:43:38.700
and feed them, and to not
close the door too soon

00:43:38.700 --> 00:43:41.390
on a kid who's seemingly
interested in nothing

00:43:41.390 --> 00:43:45.280
or a late bloomer.

00:43:45.280 --> 00:43:49.110
Lots of times early bloomers
do burn out as well.

00:43:49.110 --> 00:43:52.800
And we talked about
some of the reasons why.

00:43:52.800 --> 00:43:54.950
It's just that they
get so caught up

00:43:54.950 --> 00:43:58.110
in being that smart
kid, that they instead

00:43:58.110 --> 00:44:01.570
of taking risks and bringing
themselves to the next level

00:44:01.570 --> 00:44:06.720
constantly, and
learning to do things

00:44:06.720 --> 00:44:09.890
for the sake of learning
and doing, and being

00:44:09.890 --> 00:44:10.700
willing to fail.

00:44:10.700 --> 00:44:13.590
Instead of doing
that, they end up

00:44:13.590 --> 00:44:17.410
sort of buttressing this image
of themselves as the smart kid.

00:44:17.410 --> 00:44:20.180
So you don't take risks because
you might fail at something.

00:44:20.180 --> 00:44:22.180
And then you're not the
super smart kid anymore.

00:44:22.180 --> 00:44:23.390
You're not the whiz kid.

00:44:23.390 --> 00:44:25.360
So that's a super big problem.

00:44:25.360 --> 00:44:27.590
There's a theory
called Mindset theory

00:44:27.590 --> 00:44:30.280
that Carol Dweck
has come up with.

00:44:30.280 --> 00:44:37.700
And it's quite interesting, just
about how you encourage kids.

00:44:37.700 --> 00:44:40.410
Just as far as OK,
it's not because you're

00:44:40.410 --> 00:44:41.660
smart that you achieve things.

00:44:41.660 --> 00:44:44.030
It's because you try hard
that you achieve things.

00:44:44.030 --> 00:44:46.820
And because you're willing to
fail that you achieve things.

00:44:46.820 --> 00:44:50.660
So we often-- we make
mistakes with gifted kids,

00:44:50.660 --> 00:44:51.990
with every kid.

00:44:51.990 --> 00:44:54.120
This doesn't apply
just to gifted kids.

00:44:54.120 --> 00:44:59.620
We have to really I think be
on the lookout for these, again

00:44:59.620 --> 00:45:02.930
these sparks of talent and
interest and then feed them.

00:45:02.930 --> 00:45:05.030
And even when you're
an adult, OK, it's

00:45:05.030 --> 00:45:07.530
not your parent's
responsibility anymore,

00:45:07.530 --> 00:45:11.341
but it's our own responsibility
to find the things that

00:45:11.341 --> 00:45:13.340
make the most sense to
us and that we're good at

00:45:13.340 --> 00:45:15.600
and that we can really excel at.

00:45:19.930 --> 00:45:20.860
Yes.

